      "type": "edit",
      "id": "1e60005c49c65134",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "1e60005c49c65134",
        "text": "Whoever fights against the weak loses in any case. If he wins against them, it is a dishonorable victory. If he loses, he has lost twice... Moreover, it is true that the weak can, in principle, use any means, however unfair, without devaluing himself and his cause. The observer, i.e. the public, will be on his side (as an example, remember Gandhi's fight against the British). What the strong man does, on the other hand, is almost always inappropriate. Troops who have to fight weaker ones experience themselves as undignified, and they lose their self-respect and morale. They can no longer answer the question of meaning positively, some take drugs, some desert, etc. The professional values of soldiering lose their meaning, self-control is lost, and the repeatedly lamented atrocities occur. If they even lose to the weak, their morale is broken and so are they for good."
